R Notebook

We want to know how effective a statistical modelling approach would have been at identifying the synthetic opioid overdose epidemic, which saw its beginnings around 2012. We shall apply linear regression in order to use historical data to predict synthetic opioid overdose death rates for the years 2014 through 2018. Given the concentration of the epidemic to the east coast, we shall limit our analyses to just the portion of the US east of the Mississippi River. Due to reporting standards, much of the overdose data to the West is “suppressed” by the CDC.

Load the Data


data <- read.csv("Data/Final_Dataset_2018.csv", header = T)

Cleaning the Data

We need to modify the data slightly, this includes some basic imputation as well as the creation of a few additional variables.


## New Variables

## State, note that the first two digits (the ten-thousand and thousand place) of the county code are the state code
data$state <- factor(floor(data$county_code/1000))

threshold <- 10
data_counties <- read.table("Data/county_adjacency.txt", sep = '\t', header = F)

cnty <- NA

data$neighbor_synthetic_outbreak <- F
data$neighbor_highest_synthetic_opioid_death_rate <- 0

for(i in 1:nrow(data_counties)){
  
  if(!is.na(data_counties$V2[i])){
    cnty <- data_counties$V2[i]
  }else{
    data_counties$V2[i] <- cnty
  }
  
}


for(fips in unique(data_counties$V2)){
  
  neighbors <- data_counties[data_counties$V2 == fips,][-1,]
  
  
  for(year in 2010:2017){
    highest <- 0
    for(fips_neighbor in unique(neighbors$V4)){
      
      if(length(data$synthetic_opioid_crude_death_rate[data$year == year & data$county_code == fips_neighbor]) && data$synthetic_opioid_crude_death_rate[data$year == year & data$county_code == fips_neighbor] > highest){
        highest <- data$synthetic_opioid_crude_death_rate[data$year == year & data$county_code == fips_neighbor]
      }
      
    }
    data$neighbor_highest_synthetic_opioid_death_rate[data$county_code == fips & data$year == year] <- highest
  }
  
}

data$neighbor_synthetic_outbreak[data$neighbor_highest_synthetic_opioid_death_rate >= threshold] <- T


## Imputation

for(i in 1:nrow(data)){
  for(j in 1:ncol(data)){
    if(length(data[i,j]) > 0 && !is.na(data[i,j]) && data[i,j] == -999){
      data[i,j] <- NA
    }
  }
}


data$unemployment_rate[is.na(data$unemployment_rate)] <- mean(data$unemployment_rate, na.rm = T)
data$median_household_income[is.na(data$median_household_income)] <- mean(data$median_household_income, na.rm = T)
data$median_household_income <- log(data$median_household_income)
data$proportion_poverty[is.na(data$proportion_poverty)] <- mean(data$proportion_poverty, na.rm=T)
data$proportion_male[is.na(data$proportion_male)] <- mean(data$proportion_male, na.rm=T)
data$proportion_homes_no_vehicle[is.na(data$proportion_homes_no_vehicle)] <- mean(data$proportion_homes_no_vehicle, na.rm=T)
data$proportion_uninsured[is.na(data$proportion_uninsured)] <- mean(data$proportion_uninsured, na.rm = T)
data$proportion_homeowners_35perc_income[is.na(data$proportion_homeowners_35perc_income)] <- mean(data$proportion_homeowners_35perc_income, na.rm = T)
data$proportion_high_school_or_greater[is.na(data$proportion_high_school_or_greater)] <- mean(data$proportion_high_school_or_greater, na.rm = T)
data$proportion_white[is.na(data$proportion_white)] <- mean(data$proportion_white, na.rm = T)
data$population_density <- log(data$population_density)
data$population_density[data$population_density == -Inf | is.na(data$population_density)] <- median(data$population_density, na.rm = T)


data$police_violence[is.na(data$police_violence)] <- F

Defining the Regression Equation

First, we must define a regression equation to apply. Note that we have opted to exclude state/region from the model so that we can apply it to the other half of the country.


func <- next_year_synthetic_opioid_death_rate ~ (synthetic_opioid_crude_death_rate +
                                                   heroin_crude_death_rate +
                                                   cocaine_crude_death_rate +
                                                   meth_crude_death_rate +
                                                   unemployment_rate +
                                                   median_household_income +
                                                   proportion_poverty +
                                                   proportion_uninsured +
                                                   proportion_homes_no_vehicle +
                                                   proportion_homeowners_35perc_income +
                                                   proportion_white +
                                                   proportion_male + 
                                                   proportion_high_school_or_greater +
                                                   hep_c_mortality_rate +
                                                   urbanicity +
                                                   population_density +
                                                   opioid_prescriptions_per_100 +
                                                   road_access + 
                                                   urgent_care +
                                                   police_violence +
                                                   NFLIS +
                                                   year +
                                                   neighbor_synthetic_outbreak)

Continuous Metrics


results <- results[!is.na(results$observed_2014),]

MAE_2014 <- 0
RMSE_2014 <- 0

MAE_2015 <- 0
RMSE_2015 <- 0

MAE_2016 <- 0
RMSE_2016 <- 0

MAE_2017 <- 0
RMSE_2017 <- 0

MAE_2018 <- 0
RMSE_2018 <- 0


for(i in 1:nrow(test_data))
{
  MAE_2014 <- MAE_2014 + abs(results$observed_2014[i] - results$predicted_2014[i])
  RMSE_2014 <- RMSE_2014 + (results$observed_2014[i] - results$predicted_2014[i])^2
  
   MAE_2015 <- MAE_2015 + abs(results$observed_2015[i] - results$predicted_2015[i])
  RMSE_2015 <- RMSE_2015 + (results$observed_2015[i] - results$predicted_2015[i])^2
  
   MAE_2016 <- MAE_2016 + abs(results$observed_2016[i] - results$predicted_2016[i])
  RMSE_2016 <- RMSE_2016 + (results$observed_2016[i] - results$predicted_2016[i])^2
  
   MAE_2017 <- MAE_2017 + abs(results$observed_2017[i] - results$predicted_2017[i])
  RMSE_2017 <- RMSE_2017 + (results$observed_2017[i] - results$predicted_2017[i])^2
  
   MAE_2018 <- MAE_2018 + abs(results$observed_2018[i] - results$predicted_2018[i])
  RMSE_2018 <- RMSE_2018 + (results$observed_2018[i] - results$predicted_2018[i])^2
  
 
}

MAE_2014 <- round(MAE_2014/nrow(results),3)
RMSE_2014 <- round(sqrt(RMSE_2014/nrow(results)),3)
spearman_2014 <- round(cor(results$observed_2014, results$predicted_2014, method = "spearman"),3)

Predicting 2018 on the Western US

Now we will apply our model trained up to 2017 to try to predict 2018 rates on the west half of the country. We saved this model earlier as “lr_model_save”


## test data is west of mississippi
`%!in%` = Negate(`%in%`)


#subset the test data
test_data <- data[data$year == 2017,]
test_data <- test_data[as.numeric(as.character(test_data$state)) %!in% east_miss,]

results <- test_data[,2:3]

results$observed_2018 <- test_data$next_year_synthetic_opioid_death_rate
results$predicted_2018 <- predict(lr_model, test_data)

Top 10% Of Counties



results$observed_2018_rank[order(-results$observed_2018)] <- 1:nrow(results)


results$predicted_2018_rank[order(-results$predicted_2018)] <- 1:nrow(results)


results$observed_2018_percentile <- NA

results$predicted_2018_percentile <- NA

percentile_size <- floor(nrow(results)/10)

for(i in 1:10){
  
  threshold_lower <- (i-1)*percentile_size
  threshold_upper <- (i)*percentile_size
  
  results$observed_2018_percentile[results$observed_2018_rank > threshold_lower & results$observed_2018_rank <= threshold_upper] <- i
  
  results$predicted_2018_percentile[results$predicted_2018_rank > threshold_lower & results$predicted_2018_rank <= threshold_upper] <- i
  
}

results$observed_2018_percentile[results$observed_2018_percentile > 1] <- 2
results$predicted_2018_percentile[results$predicted_2018_percentile > 1] <- 2
